<p><strong>Kano, Nigeria (CNN)</strong> -- Hundreds of people were killed in raids by <a href='http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/17/world/africa/boko-haram-explainer/'>Boko Haram</a> Islamic militants in northeast Nigeria's Borno state, on the border with Cameroon, with some sources putting the death toll at 400 to 500.</p>
<p class="cnn_storypgraphtxt cnn_storypgraph2">On Tuesday, heavily armed men dressed as soldiers in all-terrain vehicles and on motorcycles attacked neighboring Goshe, Attagara, Agapalwa and Aganjara villages in Gwoza district, <a href='http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/04/world/africa/nigeria-boko-haram-attacks/index.html' target='_blank'>shooting residents to death and burning homes</a>.</p>
<p class="cnn_storypgraphtxt cnn_storypgraph3">The attacks forced surviving villagers to flee to Cameroon and into the Mandara Mountains on the border.</p>
<p class="cnn_storypgraphtxt cnn_storypgraph4">"The killings are massive. Nobody can say how many people were killed, but the figure runs into some hundreds," said Peter Biye, a lawmaker in Nigeria's lower parliament representing the Gwoza region.</p>
